WEBVTT

00:00.751 --> 00:02.962
[♪♪♪]

00:25.359 --> 00:26.485
Good morning.

00:27.653 --> 00:28.654
Good morning.

00:28.654 --> 00:29.947
I, uh,
stopped by the bank,

00:29.947 --> 00:31.406
they said you were here.
May I?

00:31.406 --> 00:33.033
Uh, yes. Of course.

00:33.033 --> 00:34.743
Excellent.

00:34.743 --> 00:36.119
[CLEARS THROAT]

00:36.119 --> 00:37.204
So...

00:37.204 --> 00:38.372
what can I do for you?

00:38.372 --> 00:39.581
[CHUCKLES]

00:39.581 --> 00:41.458
What we do every Monday.
It's payday.

00:41.458 --> 00:42.793
Yes, about that...

00:42.793 --> 00:44.169
What about that?

00:44.169 --> 00:46.839
[SIGHS]
Our main branch
in Cape Fullerton

00:46.839 --> 00:48.549
fell behind
in transferring cash.

00:48.549 --> 00:51.050
I, uh... I don't have
your payroll.

00:51.050 --> 00:53.178
You don't have my payroll?
But I will.

00:53.178 --> 00:55.138
Soon.
But it's Monday.

00:55.138 --> 00:56.640
I always pay my men
on Mondays.

00:56.640 --> 00:59.018
It's been that way
since I opened the sawmill.

00:59.018 --> 01:01.061
I'm proud to say
we've always been there

01:01.061 --> 01:03.731
to provide the cash.
Until today.

01:03.731 --> 01:05.399
Yes, well...

01:05.399 --> 01:07.735
I'll have your payroll
on Thursday.

01:07.735 --> 01:10.487
[SIGHS]
Look, I don't mean
to sound annoyed--

01:10.487 --> 01:12.990
No, wait, that's not true,
I am really annoyed.

01:12.990 --> 01:14.909
This is absolutely
unacceptable.

01:16.618 --> 01:19.663
It sounds like you've forgotten
it was our bank that lent you

01:19.663 --> 01:22.165
the money to open that sawmill
in the first place.

01:22.165 --> 01:24.292
In those early days,
when times got tough,

01:24.292 --> 01:26.003
we always worked with you.

01:28.338 --> 01:30.883
You did,
and I am grateful.

01:30.883 --> 01:32.259
Good.

01:32.259 --> 01:34.553
So, now we just need you
to work with us.

01:34.553 --> 01:37.806
We just need a few days to get
things straightened out.

01:38.640 --> 01:41.018
Okay, that's fair.

01:41.018 --> 01:43.353
I'll see what I can figure out
for my men.

01:44.855 --> 01:46.523
[SIGHS]

01:52.780 --> 01:55.074
[DOOR CLOSES]

01:58.535 --> 01:59.828
Katie...

01:59.828 --> 02:02.205
do you have any more
construction paper?

02:02.205 --> 02:03.749
I think you've
cleaned me out,

02:03.749 --> 02:04.708
but I'll check.

02:04.708 --> 02:05.751
Thank you.

02:05.751 --> 02:06.794
Yeah.

02:06.794 --> 02:08.629
[DOOR CLOSES]

02:08.629 --> 02:10.672
[♪♪♪]

02:10.672 --> 02:11.966
Oh, Elizabeth!

02:11.966 --> 02:13.133
What is it, Florence?

02:13.133 --> 02:14.885
You have to come with me,
right now.

02:14.885 --> 02:16.386
Oh.
Right now.

02:16.386 --> 02:17.638
Oh, my--

02:28.857 --> 02:30.484
Jack!

02:30.484 --> 02:32.277
Jack!

02:32.277 --> 02:33.403
Jack!

02:36.115 --> 02:37.240
Jack...

02:40.243 --> 02:41.954
What's going on?

02:41.954 --> 02:44.039
We've secured
the Northern Territories.

02:44.039 --> 02:45.499
We're heading home, ma'am.

02:45.499 --> 02:47.459
Have you seen
Jack Thornton?

02:47.459 --> 02:49.003
I don't know the name.

02:56.468 --> 02:57.928
[WHIMPERS]

03:07.270 --> 03:08.689
Jack!

03:14.277 --> 03:15.904
[SIGHS]

03:19.116 --> 03:21.827
I'm looking
for a Jack Thornton?

03:21.827 --> 03:23.787
He commanded a squad?

03:26.331 --> 03:28.709
What?

03:30.044 --> 03:32.671
We had a few squads...

03:32.671 --> 03:34.756
and we took some losses.

03:37.009 --> 03:38.593
[SOBS]

04:02.325 --> 04:03.493
Jack!

04:20.260 --> 04:22.387
I'm home.

04:28.560 --> 04:30.771
[♪♪♪]

04:48.914 --> 04:50.707
Oh, welcome home, Jack.

04:50.707 --> 04:52.126
Thanks, Abigail.

04:52.126 --> 04:54.419
Got the gangs and gunrunners
under control?

04:54.419 --> 04:55.420
It wasn't easy,
but yes.

04:55.420 --> 04:56.630
Well done.

04:56.630 --> 04:59.549
There he is!
A sight for sore eyes.

04:59.549 --> 05:00.717
Jack, how you
doing, pal?

05:00.717 --> 05:02.219
Hey, Lee.
Good to see you.

05:02.219 --> 05:03.303
You too.

05:03.303 --> 05:04.471
You look like
you've lost weight.

05:04.471 --> 05:05.806
Oh, he looks
great to me.

05:05.806 --> 05:07.307
You'll need
to fatten him up.

05:07.307 --> 05:08.600
I can give you
some recipes.

05:08.600 --> 05:10.144
Rosemary,
I'll be fine.

05:10.144 --> 05:12.020
I can't believe
you're finally home.

05:12.020 --> 05:13.230
Honestly, neither can I.

05:13.230 --> 05:14.689
No rush getting
back to work.

05:14.689 --> 05:16.524
Just...relax a bit.

05:16.524 --> 05:18.318
I'll take you up on that.

05:18.318 --> 05:20.361
I could teach
your class today.

05:20.361 --> 05:22.572
It could be a lesson
about social etiquette.

05:22.572 --> 05:24.365
Something
they sorely lack.

05:24.365 --> 05:26.367
As much as my students
would love that,

05:26.367 --> 05:27.911
Florence has already
volunteered.

05:27.911 --> 05:29.496
She'll be with them
until lunch.

05:29.496 --> 05:31.623
Don't waste your morning on us.
Go on.

05:31.623 --> 05:32.833
Go on,
get outta here.

05:32.833 --> 05:35.669
Go. Go have fun.

06:05.490 --> 06:07.117
Rosemary? I'm so sorry,

06:07.117 --> 06:09.619
but I still need 10 minutes
to finish this dress.

06:09.619 --> 06:11.038
No problem, Clara.

06:11.038 --> 06:12.497
It's a beautiful day.

06:12.497 --> 06:13.874
The sun is shining.

06:13.874 --> 06:15.416
My heart is full!

06:15.416 --> 06:16.417
Work your magic.

06:16.417 --> 06:17.627
Thanks.

06:18.837 --> 06:21.048
[♪♪♪]

06:26.678 --> 06:28.096
Look at you.

06:28.096 --> 06:30.473
The perfect combination
of Broadway girl

06:30.473 --> 06:32.017
and frontier woman.

06:32.017 --> 06:33.894
Sofia! Oh!

06:35.896 --> 06:38.106
It is so good to see you!

06:38.106 --> 06:39.233
You too.

06:39.233 --> 06:40.859
You look wonderful, Rosemary.

06:40.859 --> 06:43.237
And you look ravishing,
as always.

06:43.237 --> 06:45.404
I thought you weren't arriving
until tomorrow.

06:45.404 --> 06:48.158
I couldn't wait to get out
and spend some time with you.

06:48.158 --> 06:50.952
It's nothing like New York,
but it's beautiful here.

06:50.952 --> 06:53.621
It is. It's a little rough
around the edges,

06:53.621 --> 06:55.165
but there's no place like it.

06:55.165 --> 06:57.084
What's with the sea of red
leaving town?

06:57.084 --> 06:59.253
The Northern Territories
are under control.

06:59.253 --> 07:01.338
So now there's two reasons
to celebrate!

07:01.338 --> 07:02.714
[BOTH GIGGLING]

07:04.091 --> 07:05.842
Oh...

07:10.055 --> 07:13.100
[CHUCKLING AND SIGHING]

07:14.517 --> 07:16.477
I've waited
so long for this.

07:16.477 --> 07:18.563
It's good
to be home.

07:18.563 --> 07:20.690
Now we can go back
to where we were.

07:20.690 --> 07:22.067
No.

07:22.067 --> 07:23.693
No?

07:23.693 --> 07:25.612
I don't want
to be engaged.

07:25.612 --> 07:27.072
What?

07:27.072 --> 07:29.116
I want to get married,

07:29.116 --> 07:31.034
and build the house,
start a family.

07:31.034 --> 07:32.953
Okay, catch your breath.

07:32.953 --> 07:34.746
I don't need to.

07:34.746 --> 07:36.497
The thought
of coming home to you

07:36.497 --> 07:38.417
and having you there every day,

07:38.417 --> 07:40.168
it energizes me.

07:40.168 --> 07:41.211
[CHUCKLES]

07:41.211 --> 07:43.338
It got me through some...

07:43.338 --> 07:45.465
some rough times.

07:47.134 --> 07:48.509
How bad was it, Jack?

07:48.509 --> 07:49.594
It was what it was.

07:49.594 --> 07:50.887
And what was that?

07:50.887 --> 07:52.806
It's over now.

07:52.806 --> 07:54.266
I want to hear about it.

07:54.266 --> 07:55.976
Let's talk about
something else.

07:55.976 --> 07:57.936
In fact,

07:57.936 --> 07:59.562
I want to show you something.

08:09.990 --> 08:12.117
It was nice of
Mr. Coulter to hire you.

08:12.117 --> 08:14.077
Well, if giving me
a menial job

08:14.077 --> 08:15.703
with menial pay is nice,

08:15.703 --> 08:17.747
then yeah,
he's a prince.

08:17.747 --> 08:20.000
At least
it's a paycheck.

08:20.000 --> 08:22.127
True enough.

08:22.127 --> 08:25.046
Uh, gentlemen, can I have
your attention for a minute?

08:25.046 --> 08:26.631
I have an announcement.

08:26.631 --> 08:28.216
[SIGHS HEAVILY]

08:28.216 --> 08:31.594
I'm sorry to say you will not
be getting paid today.

08:31.594 --> 08:33.805
[MUTTERS]
Life keeps getting better...

08:33.805 --> 08:36.099
Now, it's just temporary.
I've been promised

08:36.099 --> 08:38.185
the payroll will be here
on Thursday.

08:38.185 --> 08:41.313
So nothing to worry about,
everything's going to be okay.

08:41.313 --> 08:43.898
If anyone has
an emergency need for cash,

08:43.898 --> 08:46.860
I do have some of my own funds
that I can advance.

08:46.860 --> 08:48.695
So, if that's you,

08:48.695 --> 08:50.947
come see me after work.

08:50.947 --> 08:52.866
Again, I'm sorry.

08:52.866 --> 08:54.242
Ahem.

08:57.412 --> 08:58.872
Can you believe that?

08:58.872 --> 09:00.665
Well, he said
he was promised

09:00.665 --> 09:03.668
that the payroll would
be here on Thursday.

09:03.668 --> 09:06.421
What's your point?

09:06.421 --> 09:09.090
It has to be the bank.

09:10.842 --> 09:12.927
Has this ever
happened before?

09:12.927 --> 09:14.595
Nah...

09:14.595 --> 09:17.391
Mr. Coulter
always pays on time.

09:25.023 --> 09:27.150
ELIZABETH:
I can't tell you
how many times

09:27.150 --> 09:28.443
I've come out here,

09:28.443 --> 09:29.903
just dreaming
of our future.

09:29.903 --> 09:31.488
Well, it's time
to stop dreaming

09:31.488 --> 09:33.031
and start building.

09:33.031 --> 09:34.824
What's this?

09:34.824 --> 09:36.284
A rough blueprint.

09:36.284 --> 09:38.870
I spent all my spare time
thinking about it.

09:38.870 --> 09:41.540
The front entrance
is gonna face east,

09:41.540 --> 09:43.124
so we get the morning sun.

09:43.124 --> 09:45.626
Don't worry, we're gonna
have a porch facing west,

09:45.626 --> 09:48.463
so we can enjoy the sunsets.
There are so many rooms.

09:48.463 --> 09:51.132
Our family's
going to grow, right?

09:51.132 --> 09:53.468
Apparently, by a lot.

09:53.468 --> 09:55.178
[SIGHS]

09:55.178 --> 09:57.222
This is really happening.

09:57.222 --> 10:01.059
Well, I've got to talk to Lee
about the lumber,

10:01.059 --> 10:02.310
but, yeah.

10:02.310 --> 10:05.230
Jack, this is just
so much, so fast.

10:05.230 --> 10:07.023
Are you sure
you don't need to rest?

10:07.023 --> 10:08.275
You must be exhausted.

10:08.275 --> 10:09.359
I'm fine.

10:09.359 --> 10:10.818
I want to put
a sitting room

10:10.818 --> 10:11.945
right here,

10:11.945 --> 10:13.488
a big dining room
right here.

10:13.488 --> 10:14.531
How big?

10:14.531 --> 10:16.199
Well...

10:16.199 --> 10:19.202
big enough to hold
all the Thornton clan.

10:21.788 --> 10:25.459
I wish I could stay out here
with you all day,

10:25.459 --> 10:27.544
but I have to get back.

10:27.544 --> 10:30.046
But seeing as how you have
all this energy, though,

10:30.046 --> 10:32.424
there is something
you could help me with.

10:32.424 --> 10:34.342
Sure, what do you need?

10:37.804 --> 10:42.683
All right, some of you did
a very good job on your tests...

10:42.683 --> 10:45.645
and some of you have room
for improvement.

10:45.645 --> 10:46.980
But the good news is,

10:46.980 --> 10:49.983
it's easy to improve
your grammar skills.

10:49.983 --> 10:55.029
All it takes is
a little bit of practice.

10:55.029 --> 10:57.031
You only got a D?

10:57.031 --> 10:59.117
So what?
What did you get?

10:59.117 --> 11:00.619
It's not that hard,
you know.

11:00.619 --> 11:02.120
You just have to study.

11:02.120 --> 11:03.371
HARPER:
I studied some.

11:03.371 --> 11:05.540
ANNA: Not enough, obviously--
Anna?

11:05.540 --> 11:08.585
What did I say about everyone
learning at their own pace?

11:08.585 --> 11:10.337
Sorry, Miss Thatcher.

11:12.464 --> 11:14.007
Don't worry, Harper.

11:14.007 --> 11:16.510
There will be another test
the day after tomorrow.

11:16.510 --> 11:18.011
Why don't you stay after class,

11:18.011 --> 11:20.221
and we can talk about
how best to prepare?

11:20.221 --> 11:21.848
Thanks.

11:29.648 --> 11:31.024
Mountie Jack!

11:31.024 --> 11:33.151
Yes, class, why don't we say
"Welcome back"?

11:33.151 --> 11:35.612
CLASS:
Welcome back!

11:35.612 --> 11:36.946
How long are you back for?

11:36.946 --> 11:38.532
My deployment is done.

11:38.532 --> 11:39.698
Your what?

11:39.698 --> 11:41.784
ELIZABETH:
That means Mountie Jack

11:41.784 --> 11:43.828
is finished
what he set out to do.

11:43.828 --> 11:44.996
He's home.

11:44.996 --> 11:46.747
CLASS:
Yay!

11:46.747 --> 11:48.791
I'll second that.
JACK: Thanks.

11:48.791 --> 11:50.544
So...about this?

11:50.544 --> 11:52.629
Oh, yeah, you can just
put it right here.

11:52.629 --> 11:54.005
What's that,
Mountie Jack?

11:54.005 --> 11:56.883
Miss Thatcher will explain.

11:56.883 --> 11:58.593
I'll bet
it's a sewing machine.

11:58.593 --> 12:00.719
Why would we need
a sewing machine?

12:00.719 --> 12:02.763
We're not sewing,
are we?

12:02.763 --> 12:05.266
Why don't you just
let me show you what it is?

12:05.266 --> 12:07.519
Are you ready?
CLASS: Yeah!

12:07.519 --> 12:09.145
All right.

12:10.522 --> 12:12.232
Ta-da!

12:13.858 --> 12:15.652
What is it?

12:15.652 --> 12:17.945
It's a mimeograph machine.

12:17.945 --> 12:18.946
What does it do?

12:18.946 --> 12:20.407
It makes
paper copies.

12:20.407 --> 12:21.908
They use them for newspapers.

12:21.908 --> 12:23.493
That's where this one
came from.

12:23.493 --> 12:25.412
The newspaper bought
a newer model,

12:25.412 --> 12:26.996
so they donated this one.

12:26.996 --> 12:28.415
What are we
gonna do with it?

12:28.415 --> 12:29.790
That's a very good question.

12:29.790 --> 12:31.668
As a part of our lesson
in journalism,

12:31.668 --> 12:34.504
we are all going to write
a school newsletter.

12:34.504 --> 12:36.839
It's our version
of a school newspaper.

12:36.839 --> 12:39.092
So, we'll all work together
to write stories,

12:39.092 --> 12:42.220
and then we will print them out
for the class to read.

12:42.220 --> 12:43.555
What kind of stories?

12:43.555 --> 12:45.724
That is a question
for your editor,

12:45.724 --> 12:47.975
the person in charge
of the newsletter.

12:47.975 --> 12:49.768
Now, do I have any volunteers--

12:49.768 --> 12:51.521
Oh.

12:51.521 --> 12:53.314
Well, all right, Hattie,

12:53.314 --> 12:56.067
it looks like you've got
the job. Congratulations.

12:56.067 --> 12:58.445
Thank you, Miss Thatcher.
I love writing stories.

12:58.445 --> 12:59.862
Good.
For this newsletter,

12:59.862 --> 13:01.489
we're going to be
gathering facts,

13:01.489 --> 13:03.824
and reporting them accurately.
Can you handle that?

13:03.824 --> 13:05.076
Absolutely.

13:06.411 --> 13:07.704
[CHUCKLES]

13:12.709 --> 13:15.754
You are a trailblazer,
my friend.

13:15.754 --> 13:17.672
Ah. Thank you.

13:17.672 --> 13:19.758
How many
female architects are there?

13:19.758 --> 13:21.050
Five? Maybe 10?

13:21.050 --> 13:23.720
Oh, I'm not sure.
Not many.
Hm.

13:23.720 --> 13:26.347
How many buildings
have you designed so far?

13:26.347 --> 13:28.182
Oh, let's see...

13:28.182 --> 13:30.393
Uh, exactly...

13:30.393 --> 13:31.394
zero.

13:31.394 --> 13:32.395
What?

13:32.395 --> 13:34.147
But...

13:34.147 --> 13:36.316
you've been a licensed
for over a year.

13:36.316 --> 13:37.816
And in that time,

13:37.816 --> 13:40.361
I've applied for nine jobs,
had four interviews,

13:40.361 --> 13:43.072
three rejections,
and one courtship proposal.

13:43.072 --> 13:44.616
[SIGHS]

13:44.616 --> 13:46.951
Well, I guess it's not easy
being a trailblazer.

13:46.951 --> 13:49.537
No. It definitely
is not.

13:49.537 --> 13:51.456
You'll land on your feet.

13:51.456 --> 13:54.125
Well,
the question is where.

13:54.125 --> 13:56.670
New York has not been
welcoming to me.

13:56.670 --> 13:58.004
You're as free as a bird.

13:58.004 --> 14:00.131
My advice is
spread your wings and fly.

14:00.131 --> 14:02.759
I'll see which way
the wind blows.

14:02.759 --> 14:04.885
Now the wind is blowing you
to Hope Valley.

14:04.885 --> 14:07.305
I am going to make sure
you have a fabulous time.

14:07.305 --> 14:09.182
[CHUCKLING]

14:09.182 --> 14:11.768
We have to come up with
stories for the newsletter.

14:11.768 --> 14:14.853
This is our first issue,
so they have to be really good.

14:14.853 --> 14:16.063
Any ideas?

14:16.063 --> 14:17.691
Harper hit a home run
last week?

14:17.691 --> 14:19.066
There are lots of tadpoles
in Spring Lake.

14:19.066 --> 14:20.485
I could write about that.

14:20.485 --> 14:22.862
I found a pinecone
that looked like a chicken.

14:22.862 --> 14:24.698
[IMITATES CHICKEN]
[CLASS LAUGHS]

14:24.698 --> 14:27.283
HATTIE:
Those are all good ideas,

14:27.283 --> 14:30.203
but, um, we need
something really big

14:30.203 --> 14:31.496
for the front page.

14:31.496 --> 14:32.997
Anyone else?

14:32.997 --> 14:35.041
Ooh.
Robert?

14:35.041 --> 14:37.293
I can hold my breath
for 55 seconds.

14:37.293 --> 14:39.045
You wanna see?

14:44.634 --> 14:46.511
[GASPS]
Oh, okay,

14:46.511 --> 14:47.804
maybe I can't.

14:47.804 --> 14:50.181
[CLASS GIGGLES]

14:51.307 --> 14:53.267
Okay...

14:59.315 --> 15:01.651
I never knew how much
I'd miss this place.

15:01.651 --> 15:04.404
Well, you don't hear that
very often about jail.

15:04.404 --> 15:06.947
Well, this is the Ritz
compared to where I've been.

15:06.947 --> 15:09.450
Yeah, I heard
the reports.

15:09.450 --> 15:12.453
I know the Mounties lost
a lot of good men up there.

15:12.453 --> 15:14.414
Yeah...

15:14.414 --> 15:16.457
Have you made a pot
of that strong coffee

15:16.457 --> 15:17.917
you're known for?

15:17.917 --> 15:19.669
Comin' up.

15:22.547 --> 15:24.215
[COFFEE POURING]

15:30.263 --> 15:31.639
It was bad, wasn't it?

15:32.515 --> 15:34.392
That's all behind me now.

15:34.392 --> 15:36.018
Is it?

15:36.770 --> 15:38.020
Yeah.

15:38.020 --> 15:39.814
Jack...

15:39.814 --> 15:41.733
if you ever want
to talk about it...

15:44.360 --> 15:47.781
I just want to get
on with my life, Bill.

15:55.288 --> 15:59.333
I heard Mr. Coulter had trouble
paying his workers.

15:59.333 --> 16:01.043
That can't be true.
I heard it from

16:01.043 --> 16:03.463
three different people.
It must be true.

16:03.463 --> 16:05.506
Do you think the sawmill
is in trouble?

16:05.506 --> 16:07.341
It couldn't close,
could it?

16:07.341 --> 16:09.719
Imagine what that would
do to Hope Valley.

16:09.719 --> 16:10.887
Remember what happened

16:10.887 --> 16:12.889
to the textile company
in Jameson?

16:12.889 --> 16:14.891
When the owner couldn't
pay his workers,

16:14.891 --> 16:15.975
it wasn't three weeks

16:15.975 --> 16:18.018
before they were
out of business.

16:18.018 --> 16:20.229
[♪♪♪]

16:26.110 --> 16:28.028
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

16:28.028 --> 16:29.948
Henry.

16:29.948 --> 16:32.366
Good to see you.
Welcome back.

16:32.366 --> 16:35.286
Why can't you make
the sawmill's payroll?

16:37.079 --> 16:40.541
Same old Henry.
Always to the point.

16:40.541 --> 16:42.543
You didn't answer the question.

16:42.543 --> 16:44.671
I don't see
it's any of your business.

16:44.671 --> 16:46.840
I work for Coulter,
but even if I didn't,

16:46.840 --> 16:49.300
I can always smell
when a problem needs fixing.

16:49.300 --> 16:50.259
[SCOFFS]

16:50.259 --> 16:51.678
Nothing needs fixing.

16:51.678 --> 16:53.972
The main branch was late
transferring the cash,

16:53.972 --> 16:57.308
that's all.
Hmm.

16:57.308 --> 17:00.520
You remember
when we used to play poker,

17:00.520 --> 17:02.605
and I would beat you every time?

17:02.605 --> 17:05.107
I don't know
that it was every time.

17:05.107 --> 17:06.693
It was.

17:06.693 --> 17:12.114
It's because I could always tell
when you were bluffing,

17:12.114 --> 17:13.867
and you're bluffing right now.

17:14.784 --> 17:16.160
The only question is,

17:16.160 --> 17:18.788
how bad is
the bank's hand?

17:20.915 --> 17:23.584
Henry, if you were
a better gambler,

17:23.584 --> 17:26.212
you wouldn't have gambled
your career and reputation

17:26.212 --> 17:28.673
to steal this town's funds.

17:31.885 --> 17:33.887
[CHILDREN CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

17:37.390 --> 17:39.099
What do you think,
Miss Thatcher?

17:39.099 --> 17:41.143
It would make
a really good cover story.

17:41.143 --> 17:43.187
Where did you get
this information, Hattie?

17:43.187 --> 17:45.732
I overheard some people
talking in the Mercantile.

17:45.732 --> 17:47.483
They said the sawmill
is gonna close.

17:47.483 --> 17:49.402
Lots of people are
gonna lose their jobs.

17:49.402 --> 17:50.904
Who exactly did you overhear?

17:50.904 --> 17:52.405
Mrs. Blakely and Miss Yost.

17:52.405 --> 17:54.240
[SIGHS]
Anyone else?

17:54.240 --> 17:55.575
No.

17:55.575 --> 17:57.785
Well, I appreciate
your enthusiasm,

17:57.785 --> 18:00.955
but do you remember
what we learned about facts?

18:00.955 --> 18:03.791
Facts should be verified
by more than one source.

18:03.791 --> 18:05.251
What you heard
was just gossip.

18:05.251 --> 18:07.127
But it would be
such a good story.

18:07.127 --> 18:09.338
It's not a good story
unless it's accurate,

18:09.338 --> 18:12.592
which means having
reliable sources, or better yet,

18:12.592 --> 18:14.969
seeing something
with your own eyes.

18:14.969 --> 18:17.055
All right, everyone inside!

18:17.055 --> 18:19.015
Recess is over!

18:31.444 --> 18:32.946
What is going on here?

18:32.946 --> 18:34.405
Excuse me.

18:34.405 --> 18:35.489
Excuse me...

18:35.489 --> 18:37.617
Pardon me.

18:39.035 --> 18:41.245
[♪♪♪]

18:45.792 --> 18:47.418
Does that make
a good headline,

18:47.418 --> 18:49.545
Miss Thatcher?

18:49.545 --> 18:50.713
It does for me.

18:50.713 --> 18:52.799
[CLASS LAUGHS]

18:54.133 --> 18:55.301
[SIGHS HAPPILY]

18:55.301 --> 18:56.844
Remember when we were 9,

18:56.844 --> 18:59.430
I built that theater for you
with wooden crates?

18:59.430 --> 19:00.848
[LAUGHS]

19:00.848 --> 19:03.059
I tap danced and sang:
♪ Oh, My Darlin' ♪

19:03.059 --> 19:04.477
♪ Oh, My Darlin' ♪

19:04.477 --> 19:07.313
♪ Oh, My Darlin' Clementine... ♪

19:07.313 --> 19:09.107
I would've loved
to have seen that.

19:09.107 --> 19:11.484
You would've had to line up.
We packed the house.

19:11.484 --> 19:12.568
I have no doubt.

19:12.568 --> 19:14.528
Sold out
three weekends in a row.

19:14.528 --> 19:15.905
In my backyard.

19:15.905 --> 19:17.490
She was a star,
even back then.

19:17.490 --> 19:19.909
Lee is going to build me
my very own theater

19:19.909 --> 19:21.201
right here in Hope Valley.

19:21.201 --> 19:22.620
Oh, really?

19:22.620 --> 19:24.998
It'll probably be made
out of wooden crates.

19:24.998 --> 19:26.415
Oh, Lee...

19:26.415 --> 19:28.126
You should design it.

19:28.126 --> 19:30.670
We could import marble
from Italy,

19:30.670 --> 19:32.713
gossamer curtains
from Paris.

19:32.713 --> 19:34.799
Oh! And those electric
theater lights

19:34.799 --> 19:36.050
that are all the rage?

19:36.050 --> 19:38.177
Rosemary has always
wanted everything

19:38.177 --> 19:39.887
to be bigger and better.

19:39.887 --> 19:42.431
Shoot for the stars,
you end up over the moon.

19:42.431 --> 19:45.225
Just look at my husband.

19:45.225 --> 19:47.645
LEE:
The man who couldn't
make payroll.

19:47.645 --> 19:49.856
Oh, that's just a little
snag with the bank.

19:49.856 --> 19:51.357
It'll sort itself out.

19:51.357 --> 19:52.692
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

19:52.692 --> 19:53.776
Hey, Carson,

19:53.776 --> 19:55.820
whatcha got there?
Ham sandwich.

19:55.820 --> 19:57.237
It's, uh, dinner.

19:57.237 --> 19:59.573
ROSEMARY:
You still taking
patients this late?

19:59.573 --> 20:02.994
Uh...no, actually,
I'm done for the day.

20:02.994 --> 20:04.912
Well, why don't you
join us then?

20:04.912 --> 20:05.955
Yes.

20:05.955 --> 20:07.623
Well, if you insist.

20:07.623 --> 20:09.125
LEE:
Please do.

20:12.170 --> 20:15.006
Sofia Connelly,
my dear old friend,

20:15.006 --> 20:17.257
meet Dr. Carson Shepherd, my--

20:17.257 --> 20:20.302
well...newer friend.

20:20.302 --> 20:21.721
[LAUGHING]

20:21.721 --> 20:23.305
It's nice to meet you,
Carson.

20:23.305 --> 20:24.891
The pleasure is mine.

20:24.891 --> 20:26.225
[CHUCKLES]

20:29.103 --> 20:30.771
Whoa.

20:30.771 --> 20:34.067
But you don't have any proof
that the bank is in danger.

20:34.067 --> 20:35.401
I know Jenkins,

20:35.401 --> 20:38.071
and, Abigail,
I'm telling you, he's lying.

20:39.739 --> 20:40.823
I'll talk to him.

20:40.823 --> 20:42.282
It's a private bank.

20:42.282 --> 20:44.744
These rich investors,
they don't report to anyone,

20:44.744 --> 20:48.831
so I don't know that you're
going to get a straight answer.

20:48.831 --> 20:50.457
Okay...

20:50.457 --> 20:53.419
let's say that you're right,
the bank is in trouble.

20:53.419 --> 20:55.588
Like you said, it's private,

20:55.588 --> 20:57.048
what would you suggest I do?

20:57.048 --> 20:58.925
Well, to protect
the town's interests,

20:58.925 --> 21:03.345
my advice would be withdraw
all the town's funds right now.

21:03.345 --> 21:05.223
Henry, if the bank
is having problems,

21:05.223 --> 21:08.350
and I take out all of our money,
it'll only mean more problems.

21:08.350 --> 21:09.560
Well, if I'm right,

21:09.560 --> 21:12.021
and my gut is telling me
that I am...

21:12.021 --> 21:14.607
well, the bank is going under.

21:17.068 --> 21:19.528
Like I said,
I'll talk to Jenkins.

21:19.528 --> 21:20.988
All right.

21:20.988 --> 21:22.990
The decision
is yours to make,

21:22.990 --> 21:26.786
but I wouldn't waste
too much time.

21:26.786 --> 21:29.914
[♪♪♪]

21:29.914 --> 21:31.916
[SIGHS]

21:37.130 --> 21:39.090
SOFIA:
Have you been
to San Francisco?

21:39.090 --> 21:41.467
It is like the wild west
meets the big city.

21:41.467 --> 21:43.261
I have always
wanted to go.

21:43.261 --> 21:44.470
Well,
I've been twice--

21:44.470 --> 21:45.805
Did you ride the cable cars?

21:45.805 --> 21:47.765
CARSON:
I was almost hit
by a cable car.

21:47.765 --> 21:49.683
That reminds me
of the time--

21:49.683 --> 21:52.270
CARSON:
...the mountains meet the water,
ferries crossing the bay...

21:52.270 --> 21:53.604
Sounds magical.

21:53.604 --> 21:55.273
It is.

21:55.273 --> 21:57.108
It definitely is.

21:57.108 --> 21:59.485
Know what, sweetheart,
I think it's getting late.

21:59.485 --> 22:01.821
Maybe we should be going home.
I'm sorry,

22:01.821 --> 22:04.406
the time just went by
so fast.

22:04.406 --> 22:07.451
Perhaps we should continue
our conversation another time.

22:07.451 --> 22:09.495
I'd like that. When?

22:09.495 --> 22:12.331
Well, if I'm not
being too forward,

22:12.331 --> 22:15.168
may I invite you to join me
for a picnic, tomorrow?

22:15.168 --> 22:17.128
Unless you two
already have plans.

22:17.128 --> 22:18.462
Do we?

22:18.462 --> 22:20.298
No, we don't.

22:20.298 --> 22:22.424
Picnic away, you two.

22:22.424 --> 22:24.010
[CHUCKLES]

22:24.010 --> 22:27.096
It looks like Dr. Shepherd
made a new friend.

22:30.266 --> 22:33.269
Oh, so he has.

22:33.269 --> 22:35.479
Know who she is?
No idea.

22:35.479 --> 22:38.565
But they seem to be getting on
rather well.

22:38.565 --> 22:40.734
CARSON:
We're gonna have to take
horses there.

22:40.734 --> 22:42.569
It's just
a little further than--

22:42.569 --> 22:44.697
We could walk there.
Just depends.

22:45.614 --> 22:47.825
[♪♪♪]

22:56.709 --> 22:58.085
Oh...

23:05.676 --> 23:08.804
Thanks for accepting
my invitation.

23:08.804 --> 23:10.973
[CHUCKLES]
Of course.

23:17.688 --> 23:20.274
[SIGHS]
Jack, this is...

23:20.274 --> 23:23.736
This is just...

23:23.736 --> 23:26.280
beautiful.

23:26.280 --> 23:27.907
May I have this dance?

23:29.200 --> 23:31.118
[LAUGHS]
There's no music.

23:31.118 --> 23:32.870
[CHUCKLES]

23:32.870 --> 23:35.289
When I was heading
to the Northern Territories

23:35.289 --> 23:36.582
with my squad,

23:36.582 --> 23:38.416
we stopped
in a small town,

23:38.416 --> 23:40.836
and I found this.

23:42.880 --> 23:45.674
I listened to it every night
before I went to sleep.

23:45.674 --> 23:47.343
It drove my squad crazy.

23:47.343 --> 23:49.595
[GIGGLES]

23:49.595 --> 23:52.181
But the thought
of dancing with you to this song

23:52.181 --> 23:55.101
kept me going...

23:55.101 --> 23:58.187
[MUSIC BOX PLAYING]

24:08.906 --> 24:12.118
Then what are you
waiting for?

24:12.118 --> 24:15.329
[♪♪♪]

24:40.938 --> 24:42.982
[RAIN PATTERING]

24:45.651 --> 24:47.861
[♪♪♪]

25:34.700 --> 25:36.869
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

25:41.539 --> 25:43.750
[♪♪♪]

26:21.121 --> 26:22.498
Well, here you go,

26:22.498 --> 26:24.833
the first load
for your new house.

26:27.211 --> 26:30.339
Wow, there is no wane
in these at all.

26:30.339 --> 26:32.925
No, nothing but the best
for the town's hero.

26:32.925 --> 26:35.344
Aw, come on, Lee,
I'm no hero.

26:36.678 --> 26:39.014
Seriously.
Okay, whatever you say, pal.

26:39.014 --> 26:41.016
Jesse's going to help you.

26:41.016 --> 26:42.726
Good to see you.
Welcome back, Jack.

26:42.726 --> 26:45.896
Thanks.
Just need you to sign
the purchase order.

26:45.896 --> 26:49.024
Wait a second, Lee, this is
not the price we agreed on.

26:49.024 --> 26:52.361
Oh, sure it is.
It's half of what we said.

26:52.361 --> 26:54.113
Jack,
you are a great Mountie,

26:54.113 --> 26:56.282
but you're a lousy negotiator.

26:56.282 --> 26:57.783
Sorry,
I can't let you do this.

26:57.783 --> 26:59.743
Yeah, you can,
and you will.

26:59.743 --> 27:01.995
It's my way of showing
a little appreciation.

27:01.995 --> 27:03.956
And don't worry,
it's at cost,

27:03.956 --> 27:06.250
so I'm not
losing any money.

27:06.250 --> 27:08.752
Go on, sign.

27:09.669 --> 27:11.380
Thanks.

27:12.339 --> 27:13.549
There we go.

27:13.549 --> 27:15.342
All right, you guys
get out of here.

27:15.342 --> 27:17.386
Okay.
All right.

27:21.307 --> 27:23.225
ABIGAIL:
Mr. Jenkins...

27:23.225 --> 27:25.144
Mrs. Stanton.

27:25.144 --> 27:27.980
Mr. Jenkins, I've been
hearing rumors about the bank.

27:27.980 --> 27:29.607
I think we should talk.

27:29.607 --> 27:32.276
I'm afraid it'll have to wait.
I was about to leave.

27:32.276 --> 27:34.778
That's why
we should talk now,

27:34.778 --> 27:38.115
or I will be forced to withdraw
all of the town's funds

27:38.115 --> 27:39.408
from your bank.

27:39.408 --> 27:41.827
[♪♪♪]

27:41.827 --> 27:45.456
Or is that
not even an option?

27:46.873 --> 27:49.585
Look...
everything will be fine.

27:49.585 --> 27:52.670
We're just a little
short of cash right now.

27:52.670 --> 27:54.298
Because..?

27:54.298 --> 27:57.134
Well, frankly, we made some
poor investment decisions.

27:57.134 --> 27:58.552
Investment decisions?

27:58.552 --> 28:00.304
Yes, that's how
the bank makes money.

28:00.304 --> 28:01.972
I know how the bank
makes money.

28:01.972 --> 28:05.434
Well, it's not unusual
to lose a little money

28:05.434 --> 28:06.810
every once in a while.

28:06.810 --> 28:08.728
How much money, Mr. Jenkins?

28:08.728 --> 28:10.564
More than I'd like.

28:10.564 --> 28:13.691
Which is why I'm traveling
to see a bank in Cape Fullerton.

28:13.691 --> 28:16.195
I'm going to ask them
for a short-term loan,

28:16.195 --> 28:18.030
just until we get
our sea legs back.

28:18.030 --> 28:19.532
What are the chances of that?

28:19.532 --> 28:20.574
Good, I hope.

28:20.574 --> 28:22.326
[GASPS]
You hope?

28:22.326 --> 28:23.701
Well, as always,

28:23.701 --> 28:26.288
the loan will come
with conditions and covenants,

28:26.288 --> 28:28.957
but it's nothing
I can't handle.

28:28.957 --> 28:32.378
Look, I've been a good citizen
of this town for many years.

28:32.378 --> 28:33.504
I even helped you

28:33.504 --> 28:35.422
get your café started.

28:35.422 --> 28:38.676
I think I've earned
a little goodwill.

28:38.676 --> 28:40.511
Okay.

28:40.511 --> 28:43.514
I will leave what's left of
the town's funds in your bank,

28:43.514 --> 28:45.015
for now.

28:45.015 --> 28:46.892
When will you be back?

28:46.892 --> 28:49.395
Tomorrow, and I promise
to bring good news.

28:49.395 --> 28:51.771
That's the only
kind of news I want to hear.

29:02.074 --> 29:04.284
[♪♪♪]

29:05.703 --> 29:09.998
Excellent job on your
grammar tests, everyone.

29:09.998 --> 29:12.125
Especially you, Harper.

29:12.125 --> 29:13.960
You should be very proud.

29:18.340 --> 29:19.758
You're right.

29:19.758 --> 29:23.053
It's not that hard
if you study.

29:23.053 --> 29:26.473
How did you go from a D
to an A-plus?

29:26.473 --> 29:28.434
Why should I
tell you?

29:28.434 --> 29:29.685
ELIZABETH:
Anna? Harper?

29:29.685 --> 29:32.229
Is there a problem,
here?

29:32.229 --> 29:33.647
No, ma'am.

29:33.647 --> 29:34.981
No.

29:35.941 --> 29:37.192
Oh, Hattie,

29:37.192 --> 29:39.152
did you find a story
for the newsletter?

29:39.152 --> 29:41.321
I have some ideas.

29:41.321 --> 29:43.490
Actually, yes.

29:43.490 --> 29:45.451
I think I found
the perfect story.

29:45.451 --> 29:47.786
Good, and did you
check your sources?

29:47.786 --> 29:49.079
I didn't have to.

29:49.079 --> 29:50.664
I saw it with my own eyes.

29:50.664 --> 29:52.040
Huh.

29:59.632 --> 30:01.967
So, who was that
you were chatting with

30:01.967 --> 30:03.469
at the café last night?

30:03.469 --> 30:04.720
Sofia?

30:04.720 --> 30:06.138
An old friend of Rosemary's.

30:06.138 --> 30:07.347
Oh.

30:07.347 --> 30:09.725
Is she staying
in Hope Valley long?

30:09.725 --> 30:12.060
CARSON:
You know,
she didn't say.

30:12.060 --> 30:14.438
FAITH:
Are you hoping
she does?

30:14.438 --> 30:17.190
CARSON:
Yeah, that might
be nice.

30:17.190 --> 30:19.901
FAITH:
It looks like
you're smitten.

30:19.901 --> 30:22.696
No, it's too soon
for that, but...

30:22.696 --> 30:25.449
who knows, right?

30:25.449 --> 30:27.660
I hope I'm not too early...

30:27.660 --> 30:29.119
No, you're right on time.

30:29.119 --> 30:30.162
Hi.

30:31.997 --> 30:35.000
Oh, you must be Sofia.

30:35.000 --> 30:36.126
And you must be Faith.

30:36.126 --> 30:37.795
I brag about
my nurse a lot.

30:37.795 --> 30:40.464
He thinks you're the best nurse
he's ever worked with.

30:40.464 --> 30:42.299
That's nice to hear.

30:42.299 --> 30:45.302
Just let me get cleaned up,
and I'll be ready to go.

30:47.012 --> 30:49.139
[CHUCKLES]

30:50.182 --> 30:52.142
It's a beautiful day
for a picnic.

30:53.018 --> 30:54.687
I hear it's going to rain,

30:54.687 --> 30:57.189
but...who knows.

30:57.189 --> 30:59.024
[CHUCKLES]

31:02.027 --> 31:03.612
You ordered
a lot of wood.

31:03.612 --> 31:06.365
It's going to be the house
Elizabeth and I live in

31:06.365 --> 31:07.907
for the rest of our lives.

31:07.907 --> 31:09.409
You're a lucky guy.

31:10.703 --> 31:13.372
And smart enough
to know how lucky.

31:17.292 --> 31:18.711
Something wrong?

31:18.711 --> 31:20.003
No.

31:22.339 --> 31:26.176
Hey, did you and Elizabeth
ever...break up?

31:26.176 --> 31:28.387
We had times
when we put things on hold.

31:28.387 --> 31:29.971
Really?

31:29.971 --> 31:32.516
That's actually where
I'm at with Clara right now.

31:32.516 --> 31:34.518
Sorry to hear that.

31:34.518 --> 31:35.769
Yeah.

31:35.769 --> 31:37.771
It was her idea.

31:38.980 --> 31:40.440
Have you tried talking to her?

31:40.440 --> 31:42.359
Not really.

31:42.359 --> 31:46.530
I mean, she called it
a break, but...

31:46.530 --> 31:50.033
[SIGHS]
I'm starting to worry
it's more permanent than that.

31:50.033 --> 31:52.619
Well, with Elizabeth,
it took a while for us to find

31:52.619 --> 31:55.581
our way back to each other,
but we got there in the end.

31:55.581 --> 31:58.709
I couldn't imagine you two
not together. Heh.

31:58.709 --> 32:01.086
If you and Clara are meant
to be, you'll find your way.

32:01.086 --> 32:03.338
How?
She asked for time,

32:03.338 --> 32:05.758
so give it to her.

32:13.390 --> 32:16.142
It's so nice to have you
home for lunch.

32:16.142 --> 32:17.853
It's nice
to be home.

32:17.853 --> 32:20.021
The tension at work
is getting pretty thick.

32:20.021 --> 32:21.481
It's not like
it's your fault

32:21.481 --> 32:23.483
the bank doesn't have funds.

32:23.483 --> 32:25.569
Not like my men
care whose fault it is.

32:25.569 --> 32:27.237
They know
they're not getting paid.

32:27.237 --> 32:29.823
Perhaps I should have
a talk with them.

32:29.823 --> 32:31.157
Set them all straight.

32:31.157 --> 32:33.243
Oh, no, no, no.
That's not a good idea,

32:33.243 --> 32:35.036
but thank you for the offer.

32:35.036 --> 32:38.498
All right. You let me know
if you change your mind.
Hm.

32:38.498 --> 32:40.959
Sofia and I
made these sandwiches

32:40.959 --> 32:44.129
for her picnic with Carson.

32:44.129 --> 32:46.548
[SIGHS]

32:46.548 --> 32:49.217
You're not going to eat.
Are you?

32:49.217 --> 32:50.510
[SIGHS]

32:50.510 --> 32:53.972
It's not that, it's just...

32:53.972 --> 32:57.100
I hope Jenkins doesn't
let us down, that's all.

32:58.226 --> 33:00.270
I should talk to your men.

33:00.270 --> 33:01.939
That's what I'll do.

33:03.022 --> 33:04.399
[SIGHS]

33:05.901 --> 33:08.403
CARSON:
How long have you wanted
to be an architect?

33:08.403 --> 33:10.322
SOFIA:
Since I was 5,

33:10.322 --> 33:13.575
I was designing
multi-level homes

33:13.575 --> 33:15.535
for my friends' dolls.

33:15.535 --> 33:18.330
CARSON:
Ah...sounds
like a calling.

33:19.122 --> 33:21.124
Maybe.

33:21.124 --> 33:23.168
What, you're not sure?

33:23.168 --> 33:25.128
I think until
you're actually doing it,

33:25.128 --> 33:27.297
it's more like a dream.

33:29.007 --> 33:31.259
Well, here's to dreamers.

33:31.259 --> 33:32.803
[CHUCKLES]

33:32.803 --> 33:36.055
May all of our dreams
become callings.

33:37.265 --> 33:38.600
[CHUCKLING]

33:40.853 --> 33:44.523
Mm, this is delicious.

33:44.523 --> 33:48.485
Well, I admit, I had some help
from Rosemary.

33:48.485 --> 33:50.529
I'm not the greatest cook.

33:50.529 --> 33:52.280
[CHUCKLING]
Well,

33:52.280 --> 33:54.199
you have to let me
cook for you sometime.

33:54.199 --> 33:56.952
You cook?
When I first came
to Hope Valley,

33:56.952 --> 33:58.495
I worked at Abigail's café.

33:58.495 --> 33:59.913
I had no idea.

33:59.913 --> 34:01.790
I make a mean chili.

34:01.790 --> 34:03.583
I will keep that in mind.

34:03.583 --> 34:04.960
[CHUCKLING]

34:06.962 --> 34:09.422
[♪♪♪]

34:09.422 --> 34:12.759
They say the eyes
are the window to the soul.

34:12.759 --> 34:14.427
Oh.

34:14.427 --> 34:15.721
Well...

34:15.721 --> 34:18.015
what do you see?

34:19.474 --> 34:21.643
Well...

34:21.643 --> 34:23.061
I'm a doctor, so...

34:24.312 --> 34:26.147
I see a scratched cornea.

34:26.147 --> 34:28.400
Ooh,
he's a smooth-talking man.

34:29.401 --> 34:31.444
What do you see?

34:32.863 --> 34:34.280
Well...

34:34.280 --> 34:37.242
I'm a licensed architect,
so...

34:37.242 --> 34:39.244
I see potential.

34:40.037 --> 34:42.080
Potential's good.

34:42.080 --> 34:43.874
I'll take that.

34:45.792 --> 34:48.545
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

34:49.546 --> 34:50.589
Uh-oh.

34:50.589 --> 34:52.549
[LAUGHING]

34:52.549 --> 34:54.133
Come...

34:54.133 --> 34:55.385
[RAIN PATTERING]

34:55.385 --> 34:56.887
[LAUGHING AND SHRIEKING]

34:56.887 --> 34:58.722
Let's go in here.
Let's go here.

35:01.058 --> 35:03.101
[BOTH LAUGHING]

35:03.101 --> 35:04.561
Here, wrap this
around you.

35:04.561 --> 35:05.979
Thanks. Oh.

35:05.979 --> 35:08.356
You okay?

35:08.356 --> 35:10.859
Never been better.

35:10.859 --> 35:12.360
[CHUCKLES]

35:18.491 --> 35:20.619
Here you are.
Thank you.

35:20.619 --> 35:22.662
Are you sure you don't
need a blanket?

35:22.662 --> 35:24.330
Really, I'm fine.

35:24.330 --> 35:26.291
I just got caught up
in a little rain.

35:26.291 --> 35:29.252
Did it ruin the picnic?

35:29.252 --> 35:31.337
Quite the contrary.

35:31.337 --> 35:34.091
All right...

35:34.091 --> 35:37.552
I see it, clear as day.
See what?

35:37.552 --> 35:39.304
"See what?"

35:39.304 --> 35:42.808
The starry eyes,
that little smile.

35:42.808 --> 35:45.102
It could only mean
one thing.

35:45.102 --> 35:46.352
What?

35:46.352 --> 35:50.107
Hope Valley has
worked its magic.

35:50.107 --> 35:52.150
Maybe.

35:52.150 --> 35:53.902
Hmm?

35:56.321 --> 35:57.906
[CHUCKLES]

36:00.909 --> 36:02.535
[♪♪♪]

36:02.535 --> 36:03.829
Breakfast...

36:03.829 --> 36:04.955
is...

36:04.955 --> 36:06.205
served.

36:07.457 --> 36:09.001
Wow.

36:09.001 --> 36:12.295
I could've fed my whole squad
with this meal.

36:12.295 --> 36:14.881
I hate to admit it,
but Rosemary was actually right.

36:14.881 --> 36:17.717
I do need
to fatten you up a bit.

36:17.717 --> 36:20.137
Are you ready
to make the announcement?

36:20.137 --> 36:22.221
Are you?

36:22.221 --> 36:23.556
Because once this gets out,

36:23.556 --> 36:25.892
things could get
a little crazy around here.

36:25.892 --> 36:27.853
I'm ready,
excited actually.

36:28.770 --> 36:30.313
Okay, then.

36:30.313 --> 36:31.648
Today after school?

36:31.648 --> 36:33.942
It's a date.

36:34.901 --> 36:36.153
[CHUCKLES]

36:40.907 --> 36:43.451
Opal, Emily,
what do you have there?

36:43.451 --> 36:45.411
It's the school's
newsletter.

36:45.411 --> 36:46.621
Who gave you that?

36:46.621 --> 36:48.915
Hattie.
She gave everybody a copy.

36:48.915 --> 36:50.876
May I see it, please?

36:50.876 --> 36:53.086
Thank you.

36:56.214 --> 36:59.134
STUDENTS [CHANTING]:
Cheater, cheater!

36:59.134 --> 37:00.552
Cheater,
you cheated!

37:00.552 --> 37:02.470
HARPER:
That's a lie!
That's not true!

37:02.470 --> 37:03.638
That's enough!

37:03.638 --> 37:05.264
What is going on here?

37:05.264 --> 37:06.766
Harper cheated
on his test.

37:06.766 --> 37:08.810
No wonder he got
such a good grade!

37:08.810 --> 37:10.020
I didn't cheat.

37:10.020 --> 37:11.938
CODY:
"Harper
snuck into the school,

37:11.938 --> 37:14.149
and copied the answers
to the grammar test."

37:14.149 --> 37:17.276
That's not true. I was returning
Miss Thatcher's study aids.

37:17.276 --> 37:18.444
Sure you were.

37:18.444 --> 37:20.155
ELIZABETH:
He's telling the truth.

37:20.155 --> 37:21.489
I lent Harper my study aids

37:21.489 --> 37:23.408
so he could improve
his grammar score.

37:23.408 --> 37:25.410
He had permission
to be in the school.

37:26.536 --> 37:28.454
Now, where's Hattie?

37:31.917 --> 37:34.086
Hattie, please come here.

37:34.086 --> 37:36.671
Everyone else,
go inside.

37:36.671 --> 37:40.050
And I want every copy
of this newsletter on my desk.

37:42.343 --> 37:44.429
Harper,
I'll take care of this.

37:47.599 --> 37:51.394
Can you please explain to me
why you printed these?

37:51.394 --> 37:53.646
I saw Harper
sneak into the school,

37:53.646 --> 37:55.440
so I followed him.

37:55.440 --> 37:58.026
When I looked inside,
I saw him at your desk.

37:58.026 --> 37:59.485
It looked suspicious.

37:59.485 --> 38:01.947
So you wrote this article
and published it?

38:01.947 --> 38:03.740
I saw him
writing the answers.

38:03.740 --> 38:06.492
You thought you saw him,
but you were mistaken.

38:06.492 --> 38:08.369
Harper was writing me
a thank-you note

38:08.369 --> 38:10.789
because I lent him
my study aids.

38:10.789 --> 38:13.458
This is why you were supposed to
show me your article

38:13.458 --> 38:15.334
before we printed these.

38:15.334 --> 38:17.254
You have any idea
how embarrassing

38:17.254 --> 38:19.214
this must be for Harper?

38:19.214 --> 38:21.925
I just wanted a good headline
for our first issue.

38:21.925 --> 38:24.010
[SIGHS]

38:24.010 --> 38:26.679
You are the editor
of the newsletter

38:26.679 --> 38:28.431
because I trusted you
to understand

38:28.431 --> 38:30.683
the importance of words.

38:30.683 --> 38:32.644
When you write something
about someone,

38:32.644 --> 38:34.938
you have to be certain
that it's true.

38:34.938 --> 38:37.774
But I saw it myself,
just like you said.

38:37.774 --> 38:40.068
But you didn't know
what you saw, did you?

38:40.068 --> 38:42.361
I guess not.

38:42.361 --> 38:45.364
Harper studied really hard
for that test,

38:45.364 --> 38:48.201
and now all of his friends
are calling him a cheater.

38:48.201 --> 38:50.453
I'm sorry, Miss Thatcher.

38:50.453 --> 38:53.623
I didn't mean to hurt anyone.
I just wanted to impress you.

38:53.623 --> 38:56.251
Well, you can still
impress me.

38:56.251 --> 38:58.086
How?

38:58.086 --> 39:01.756
HATTIE:
"...Therefore, as editor
of our school's newsletter,

39:01.756 --> 39:03.883
"I would like to apologize
to Harper Tucker

39:03.883 --> 39:06.803
"for falsely reporting that
he cheated on his grammar test.

39:06.803 --> 39:09.931
"He studied hard for that test
and deserved a perfect grade.

39:09.931 --> 39:13.143
"In future, I will be sure
that all stories are accurate

39:13.143 --> 39:16.104
before they are published."

39:16.104 --> 39:17.563
Thank you, Hattie.

39:17.563 --> 39:20.358
I hope we've all learned
an important lesson today.

39:20.358 --> 39:22.735
All right, everyone,
that's all for today.

39:22.735 --> 39:24.487
Class dismissed.

39:24.487 --> 39:28.533
[STUDENTS CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

39:28.533 --> 39:30.702
Thank you for that.

39:30.702 --> 39:34.789
But you know, sometimes,
a personal touch is also needed.

39:40.545 --> 39:42.421
I'm sorry, Harper.

39:42.421 --> 39:45.758
You should have just asked me
what I was doing.

39:45.758 --> 39:47.052
I would have
told you.

39:47.052 --> 39:48.469
I know.

39:48.469 --> 39:51.097
I was wondering...

39:51.097 --> 39:53.016
since you're so good
at grammar now,

39:53.016 --> 39:56.186
maybe you'd want to be
my assistant editor?

39:56.186 --> 39:59.647
Assistant editor
sounds pretty good.

39:59.647 --> 40:02.150
Co-editor sounds even better.

40:02.150 --> 40:05.737
Co-editor...
I like that.

40:05.737 --> 40:07.947
[♪♪♪]

40:15.496 --> 40:17.123
Hello, boys.
What's up?

40:17.123 --> 40:21.294
Lee...
I have an announcement.

40:21.294 --> 40:23.213
Jack and I
are getting married.

40:23.213 --> 40:27.259
Well, that's not
exactly big news.

40:27.259 --> 40:28.260
In two weeks.

40:28.260 --> 40:29.969
Two weeks!
BILL: What?

40:29.969 --> 40:33.139
I'd like you both to be
my Matrons of Honor.

40:33.139 --> 40:35.516
Oh, Elizabeth.

40:35.516 --> 40:36.726
Of course.

40:36.726 --> 40:38.603
[ALL LAUGHING]

40:38.603 --> 40:41.981
And I would like you both
to be my Best Men.

40:41.981 --> 40:43.358
Wow.

40:43.358 --> 40:44.817
Uh...okay.

40:44.817 --> 40:46.278
Two weeks?

40:46.278 --> 40:48.571
Oh, no, that's
not enough time

40:48.571 --> 40:50.323
to plan a wedding
of this magnitude.

40:50.323 --> 40:52.367
I'm sure we can
get it done.

40:54.702 --> 40:56.913
We'd better start planning
a bachelor party.

40:56.913 --> 40:58.164
LEE: Yeah--
Uh, no, no,

40:58.164 --> 40:59.540
I'm not sure I want
a bachelor party--

40:59.540 --> 41:01.293
LEE &amp; BILL:
You're gonna have one.

41:01.293 --> 41:02.585
Thanks.

41:02.585 --> 41:03.628
[VOICES SHOUTING]

41:03.628 --> 41:04.921
What's going on
out there?

41:04.921 --> 41:06.298
[VOICES SHOUTING]

41:06.298 --> 41:08.674
Do you hear that?

41:11.761 --> 41:13.972
[♪♪♪]

41:17.475 --> 41:20.770
Oh, no. Oh, no...
Okay...

41:25.650 --> 41:27.652
Mr. Jenkins!

41:29.862 --> 41:31.197
Mr. Jenkins, open up!

41:31.197 --> 41:32.782
[KNOCKING]

41:32.782 --> 41:34.242
Jesse...

41:35.410 --> 41:36.828
Where's Jenkins?

41:36.828 --> 41:40.081
As far as I can tell,
he's hiding inside.

41:41.416 --> 41:44.252
Abigail? Tell us
what's happening.

41:44.252 --> 41:45.670
Why isn't the bank open?

41:45.670 --> 41:48.047
It will. Soon.
I can't keep the mill open

41:48.047 --> 41:50.175
if I can't pay
my employees.

41:50.175 --> 41:52.135
We need cash
to restock our shelves.

41:52.135 --> 41:53.803
I have a new kiln
being delivered.

41:53.803 --> 41:55.180
How am I supposed
to pay?

41:55.180 --> 41:57.682
When do we get our money?
Everyone, relax.

41:57.682 --> 41:59.142
Getting excited
won't help.

41:59.142 --> 42:01.811
What will help
is having the bank open.

42:01.811 --> 42:03.562
And "soon"
isn't good enough.

42:03.562 --> 42:05.148
Abigail,
you're the mayor.

42:05.148 --> 42:07.608
What are you going
to do about this?

42:15.741 --> 42:17.952
[♪♪♪]
